                            <comment id="12971947" author="dlofthouse" created="Fri, 30 May 2014 08:32:19 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;There is no requirement to restart the server, the security domains contain a flush-cache operation that can be called to clear either the whole security domain or a selected principal from the cache.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12971949" author="jokser" created="Fri, 30 May 2014 08:42:40 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;I found this operation when I was exploring source code. But anyway it&apos;s not a good solution when roles changes frequently.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12971955" author="dlofthouse" created="Fri, 30 May 2014 08:53:26 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;It sounds like you have a good understanding of the problem and have spent some time understanding the code in this area, why not finish off your solution to make it generic and get a pull request sent over?  That way we can get your changes incorporated in master.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12971960" author="jokser" created="Fri, 30 May 2014 09:06:18 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;I never participated in opensource projects. But I will try to solve this problem on server-side level at the weekend.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12971961" author="dlofthouse" created="Fri, 30 May 2014 09:08:18 -0400"  >&lt;p&gt;Feel free to comment here if you run into any issues but overall community contributions are always welcome.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13019592" author="damaru" created="Wed, 12 Nov 2014 22:35:08 -0500"  >&lt;p&gt;Pavel Kovalenko, thanks so much for submitting that code. It totally saved my hide tonight.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My use case is: An administrator wants to change someone else&apos;s password so that they can either log in or be locked out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I didn&apos;t want to flush the cache when the current user logged out but rather when we changed someone&apos;s password. It was trivial, after looking at your code.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers,&lt;br/&gt;
Michael Davis&lt;br/&gt;
Ottawa&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
